LOS ANGELES (AP) — Southern California’s Metrolink passenger rail service added 26 trains Monday as ridership lost during the coronavirus pandemic begins to return. The new schedule also makes four Amtrak Pacific Surfliner trains available to Metrolink ticketholders, Metrolink said in a statement.“Customers across SoCal, myself included, enjoyed new flexibility in train options to get to work, important appointments, or just to have some fun,” Metrolink CEO Darren Kettle said. Metrolink is now at approximately 30% of its weekday ridership compared to pre-pandemic levels, and growth is expected to reach 44% by midsummer, the service said. On weekends, Metrolink has recovered nearly 70% of its pre-pandemic ridership.Metrolink said its trains are cleaned and disinfected multiple times daily. Face coverings continue to be required by the federal Transportation Security Administration.Metrolink has 538 miles (865.83 kilometers) of track and 62 stations across Los Angeles, Orange, Riverside, San Bernardino and Ventura counties. Metrolink said that prior to the pandemic it had nearly 12 million annual boardings.